  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Hence, models with suppressed couplings to light families have the potential to remain compatible with exiting data, even for relatively low NP scales.It is important to notice that the U(2) 5 symmetry, on its own, does not provide any specific insight into the underlying dynamics, aside from indicating the absence of flavor violation involving the light families.",
    "To characterize the class of models we are interested in, we need to make further assumptions about the parametric structure of the WCs at the high scale Λ NP.",
    "We outline these assumptions as follows:i) The WCs of operators involving light fields are subject to a suppression factor(ε Q) n Q (ε L) n L, where n Q (n L) denotes the number of light quark (lepton) fields in the operator.",
    "For example, we assume C[iijj] qe = ε 2 Q ε 2 L /Λ 2.ii) The WCs of operators containing one or more Higgs fields feature a suppression factor (ε H) n H, where n H represents the number of Higgs fields.iii) The WCs of operators that include one or more gauge field strength tensors are suppressed by ε loop = (Π i g i)/(16π 2), where the product of gauge couplings runs over the field strength tensors present in the operator.",
    "For example, C[33]dW = ε H g L /(16π 2 Λ 2) and C HB = ε 2 H g 2 Y /(16π 2 Λ 2).Only the first of these conditions is directly related to the hypothesis of NP coupled mainly to the third generation."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, C[33]dW = ε H g L /(16π 2 Λ 2) and C HB = ε 2 H g 2 Y /(16π 2 Λ 2).Only the first of these conditions is directly related to the hypothesis of NP coupled mainly to the third generation."
  ]
}